Ethnopharmacological literature review based on scholarly databases (Pubmed, Medline, SciFinder) and other supporting documents revealed that 34 of the 62 plants had been recorded for use against leishmaniasis, trypanosomiasis or malaria, including the symptoms related to any of these diseases (

